<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] Ontario
[2] Quebec
[3] Manitoba
******
[1]
Date: 30 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ontario Ministry of Health and Long Term Care, West Nile virus
update [edited]
<http://www.gov.on.ca/health/english/program/pubhealth/wnv_mn.html>

Ontario: 43 Birds Confirmed or Presumed West Nile Virus-positive
----------------------------------------------------------------
As of Tue 30 Jul 2002, a total of 38 birds have been confirmed West Nile
virus-positive and another 5 presumed positive in Ontario. The confirmed and
presumed positive birds have been found in the following regions:
Chatham-Kent (8 confirmed),
Haldimand-Norfolk (1 presumed),
Haliburton-Kawartha-Pine Ridge (1 presumed),
Halton (7 confirmed),
Hamilton (3 confirmed),
Lambton (2 presumed),
Middlesex-London (1 confirmed),
Niagara (3 confirmed),
Oxford (5 confirmed),
Peel (5 confirmed),
Perth (3 confirmed),
Toronto (1 confirmed),
Waterloo (1 confirmed),
Wellington-Dufferin-Guelph (1 presumed),
Windsor-Essex (1 confirmed).
Mosquitoes: 5 pools of mosquitoes have tested West Nile virus-positive in
Peel Region.
******
[2]
Date: 30 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Direction de sante publique de Montreal-Centre, Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://www.santepub-mtl.qc.ca/Communiques/Comm_presse/2002/
juillet200211.html>

Quebec: West Nile Virus-positive Bird Total Remains 2
--------------------------------------------------------
No additional West Nile virus-positive birds have been confirmed in Quebec
since the discovery of 2 positive American crows in Montreal,
l'arrondissement Beaconsfield - Baie d'Urfe, on 12 Jul 2002.
******
[3]
Date: 30 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manitoba Government, News Release, 26 Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://www.gov.mb.ca/chc/press/top/2002/07/2002-07-26-05.html>

Manitoba: West Nile Virus-positive Bird Total Now 10
----------------------------------------------------
On 26 Jul 2002, 2 birds in Manitoba were identified as positive for West
Nile virus. A blue jay found in the southeastern part of Winnipeg on 20 Jul
2002 is confirmed positive. In addition, a crow found in the R.M. of
Whitehead on 19 Jul 2002, is [a] presumptive positive and 10 birds in
Manitoba have now been confirmed positive for West Nile virus: Winnipeg, 4
crows, 2 blue jays and 1 raven; R.M. of St. Andrews, 1 crow; R.M. of Tache,
1 magpie; and R.M. of Whitehead, 1 crow (presumed positive).
